3768static bool objectMatchesSearchCriteriaWithResultLimit(AXCoreObject* object, AccessibilitySearchCriteria const& criteria, AXCoreObject::AccessibilityChildrenVector& results)
3769{
3770 if (isAccessibilityObjectSearchMatch(object, criteria) && isAccessibilityTextSearchMatch(object, criteria)) {
3771 results.append(object);
3772
3773 // Enough results were found to stop searching.
3774 if (results.size() >= criteria.resultsLimit)
3775 return true;
3776 }
3777
3778 return false;
3779}
3780
3781static void appendChildrenToArray(AXCoreObject* object, bool isForward, AXCoreObject* startObject, AccessibilityObject::AccessibilityChildrenVector& results)
3782{
3783 // A table's children includes elements whose own children are also the table's children (due to the way the Mac exposes tables).
3784 // The rows from the table should be queried, since those are direct descendants of the table, and they contain content.
3785 const auto& searchChildren = object->isTable() && object->isExposable() ? object->rows() : object->children();
3786
3787 size_t childrenSize = searchChildren.size();
3788
3789 size_t startIndex = isForward ? childrenSize : 0;
3790 size_t endIndex = isForward ? 0 : childrenSize;
3791
3792 // If the startObject is ignored, we should use an accessible sibling as a start element instead.
3793 if (startObject && startObject->accessibilityIsIgnored() && startObject->isDescendantOfObject(object)) {
3794 AXCoreObject* parentObject = startObject->parentObject();
3795 // Go up the parent chain to find the highest ancestor that's also being ignored.
3796 while (parentObject && parentObject->accessibilityIsIgnored()) {
3797 if (parentObject == object)
3798 break;
3799 startObject = parentObject;
3800 parentObject = parentObject->parentObject();
3801 }
3802 // Get the un-ignored sibling based on the search direction, and update the searchPosition.
3803 while (startObject && startObject->accessibilityIsIgnored())
3804 startObject = isForward ? startObject->previousSibling() : startObject->nextSibling();
3805 }
3806
3807 size_t searchPosition = startObject ? searchChildren.find(startObject) : WTF::notFound;
3808
3809 if (searchPosition != WTF::notFound) {
3810 if (isForward)
3811 endIndex = searchPosition + 1;
3812 else
3813 endIndex = searchPosition;
3814 }
3815
3816 // This is broken into two statements so that it's easier read.
3817 if (isForward) {
3818 for (size_t i = startIndex; i > endIndex; i--)
3819 appendAccessibilityObject(searchChildren.at(i - 1).get(), results);
3820 } else {
3821 for (size_t i = startIndex; i < endIndex; i++)
3822 appendAccessibilityObject(searchChildren.at(i).get(), results);
3823 }
3824}
3825
3826void findMatchingObjects(AccessibilitySearchCriteria const& criteria, AXCoreObject::AccessibilityChildrenVector& results)
3827{
3828 AXTRACE("Accessibility::findMatchingObjects");
3829 AXLOG(criteria);
3830
3831 // This search algorithm only searches the elements before/after the starting object.
3832 // It does this by stepping up the parent chain and at each level doing a DFS.
3833
3834 // If there's no start object, it means we want to search everything.
3835 AXCoreObject* startObject = criteria.startObject;
3836 if (!startObject)
3837 startObject = criteria.anchorObject;
3838
3839 bool isForward = criteria.searchDirection == AccessibilitySearchDirection::Next;
3840
3841 // The first iteration of the outer loop will examine the children of the start object for matches. However, when
3842 // iterating backwards, the start object children should not be considered, so the loop is skipped ahead. We make an
3843 // exception when no start object was specified because we want to search everything regardless of search direction.
3844 AXCoreObject* previousObject = nullptr;
3845 if (!isForward && startObject != criteria.anchorObject) {
3846 previousObject = startObject;
3847 startObject = startObject->parentObjectUnignored();
3848 }
3849
3850 // The outer loop steps up the parent chain each time (unignored is important here because otherwise elements would be searched twice)
3851 for (auto* stopSearchElement = criteria.anchorObject->parentObjectUnignored(); startObject && startObject != stopSearchElement; startObject = startObject->parentObjectUnignored()) {
3852 // Only append the children after/before the previous element, so that the search does not check elements that are
3853 // already behind/ahead of start element.
3854 AXCoreObject::AccessibilityChildrenVector searchStack;
3855 if (!criteria.immediateDescendantsOnly || startObject == criteria.anchorObject)
3856 appendChildrenToArray(startObject, isForward, previousObject, searchStack);
3857
3858 // This now does a DFS at the current level of the parent.
3859 while (!searchStack.isEmpty()) {
3860 AXCoreObject* searchObject = searchStack.last().get();
3861 searchStack.removeLast();
3862
3863 if (objectMatchesSearchCriteriaWithResultLimit(searchObject, criteria, results))
3864 break;
3865
3866 if (!criteria.immediateDescendantsOnly)
3867 appendChildrenToArray(searchObject, isForward, 0, searchStack);
3868 }
3869
3870 if (results.size() >= criteria.resultsLimit)
3871 break;
3872
3873 // When moving backwards, the parent object needs to be checked, because technically it's "before" the starting element.
3874 if (!isForward && startObject != criteria.anchorObject && objectMatchesSearchCriteriaWithResultLimit(startObject, criteria, results))
3875 break;
3876
3877 previousObject = startObject;
3878 }
3879
3880 AXLOG(results);
3881}
